sentences: Curley Williams (b. Dock Williams, June 3, 1914 – d. September 5, 1970) was an American country and western musician and songwriter from Georgia.
Curley Williams (b. Dock Williams, June 3, 1914 – d. September 5, 1970) was an American country and western musician and songwriter from Georgia.
He was admitted to the Atlanta Country Music Hall of Fame in 1999.
Around 1940 Williams debuted with a band named The Santa Fe Trail Riders on WPAX in Thomasville, Georgia.
In December 1942 the band was invited to join the cast of the Grand Ole Opry.
The Georgia Peach Pickers agreed a recording contract with Columbia Records in 1943 and remained associated with Columbia into the 1950s.
The Georgia Peach Pickers agreed a recording contract with Columbia Records in 1943 and remained associated with Columbia into the 1950s.
During a tour of California they appeared in the 1947 film "Riders of the Lone Star" starring Charles Starrett.

Williams' best-known song, "Half As Much" was written in 1950 while he and his band were working with the WHMA radio station, which broadcast to the Alabama cities of Anniston, Birmingham, Montgomery and Dothan.
Reputedly, Williams wrote and recorded a demo of "Half as Much" very quickly, in about an hour, at WHMA in Dothan.
Williams moved to WSFA in Montgomery in 1953.
He stayed in Montgomery until he died in 1970.
For a couple of years he also had a show on WCOV-TV, and he ran a country night club called "The Spur".
